stork.feather.net

Class Coder<A,B>

  • java.lang.Object
    • stork.feather.net.Coder<A,B>
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    Socket

    public abstract class Coder<A,B>
extends Object
    A Coder<A,B> transcodes messages of type A into messages of type B. A Coder<A,B> can be joined with a Coder<B,C> to produce a Coder<A,C>.

      • pause

        public final void pause(Bell<?> bell)
        Pause messages from this coder until bell rings. Once this is called, messages will not emitted to the next coder until the bell rings.

      • code

        protected abstract void code(A a)
                      throws Throwable
        Handle coding a message fed into the coder. Once this has been called, the handling of this message is the responsibility of the coder. If an exception is thrown here, code(Throwable) will be called.
        Throws:
        Throwable

      • code

        protected void code(Throwable error)
             throws Throwable
        Code an error fed into the coder. If this throws, the thrown error is propagated downward.
        Throws:
        Throwable

      • join

        public final <C> Coder<A,C> join(Coder<B,C> coder)
        Join this Coder<A,B> with a Coder<B,C> coder to create a Coder<A,C>. Output from the Coder<A,B> will be fed to the Coder<B,C>. After joining, the Coders are "used up", and should not be used individually. Instead, all interaction with the Coders should take place through the returned composed Coder.

      • combine

        public final Codec<A,B> combine(Coder<B,A> decoder)
        Combine this Coder<A,B> with a Coder<B,A> to produce a Codec<A,B>.

      • loop

        public static <X> Coder<X,X> loop(Coder<X,X> coder)
        Join a Coder<X,X> to itself. This is equivalent to doing codec.join(codec), though without needing an intermediate variable.
